message.content: Cubing both sides of the equation $\displaystyle \sqrt[3]{3-x }=-\frac{3}{2}$, we find $\displaystyle 3-x=-\frac{27}{8}$.  Solving this equation for $x$ gives $\displaystyle x = \frac{51}{8}$.  Checking, we see that this is a valid solution.  Thus, the equation $\displaystyle \sqrt[3]{3-x }=-\frac{3}{2}$ has just one solution, $\displaystyle x = \frac{51}{8}$.
